One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what is happening in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line, a majority of the American governments promulgated, from 2009, new laws that made the process of registration or voting difficult.
This phenomenon has spread since the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states during 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, those laws reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as an electorate on the day of polling and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit a photo identity document.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana law.
For this reason, the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo identity document.
It is important to note that, unlike what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not have any identity papers with photographs issued by a government agency of their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
Thus, new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 per year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have a photo identity document.
And there's even more.
In many states students, voters who most vote for democratic candidates cannot use the photographed identity document issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote on Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004 no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two of the three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of polling in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service to voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, election registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favour the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13 per cent of the state voters.
In the case of Hispanics it was exactly the same.
They represent only 11 per cent of voters, representing 24 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Ministry of Tax intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, it was possible to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the submission of a photographed identity document.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the results of 2012 in the key states.
A report by the Brennan Centre of 2011 shows that the states that have adopted those laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too soon to assert with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system scale will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
