The Facebook social network also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositors of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins changes consist of the public account book, which spreads across the network.
The key point is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is due to the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file-cutting, i.e. transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cook" the new transaction and add a number before "twrinkling" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the mark.
If, to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very fast (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different tracks.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the one-hundredth, which leaves a broad margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in the power of calculation.
The life of the network already has its heights.
