A Constitution with Forums in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever with respect to the constitutional declaration, which gives it provisionally full powers, he decided to play the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote for its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt has used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial shocks.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues "treasoning his word" and "twisting the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to bring the institutional and political crisis to an end and accelerate the transition process.
In the next 15 days a referendum should be held.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to give up their draft explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to recover a popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy causes havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview to the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains a ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or vote on my text or keep full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, a vast majority of Islamist, voted the text yesterday.
The majority of the Liberals did not reach the call.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not make their views valued.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the quorum required, 11 people, substitute members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
On the other hand, the commentators are grateful that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed almost at the time of the prayer, so that several members of the committee came to think that the time of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law, remains the same as that of the Constitution of 1971."
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the norms", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than an advertising squabbling.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is made through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who must confirm his conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next director of this university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
The majority of the jurists who have worked on this text are not olemmas but university students, some of whom are trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might be raised in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to pronounce themselves above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers entrusted to the President of the Republic.
Muslim Brothers will claim that there are few compared to those during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
As the military wishes, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Civil prosecutions in military courts will not be prohibited either, as requested by human rights associations.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberal.
Blasphemy is maintained and now insults are banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, reports Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive was the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to leave last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state manifested themselves on Saturday.
