Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries last week Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member of ESA of the former Eastern Europe bloc after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the Agency's project commission.
However, Poland’s way to the cosmos started a long time earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before the Second World War, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the participants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the award Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a major promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was put on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a dredgedina was built in Poland, which was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known, nor are the project details known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the drain or for its braking.
Information about this Dresin is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the stored material, it is evident that the investigation reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committeeet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemmy, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society that would devote itself to cosmonautics was proposed.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) had aspired to become a member of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronauticals.
He completed this post until his death in 1959.
As of 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna) rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 metres, about 80 cm in length and did not reach the 5 kg weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and the two-stage RM-2 rocket air tests started in the Błędów desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the height wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first rockets of the RM type was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from one another by space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, at the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and at the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket, the first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km of height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Commission for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the research into the cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
