In November 1979 a group of Islamist students held the American Embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who, after the revolution, fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer any positive perspective: throwing the shah over the edge could not be allowed, since, if it did, it would endanger the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified even more with the failed attempt to free hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the U.S., their destiny caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
The failure in Iran made a decisive contribution to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in front of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film "Argo" by the director and actor Ben Affleck discusses an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before taking up the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated periple, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, thus helping a covert story: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combination
The plan by the expert in "exfiltration" Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
For the lie to seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized journals, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of various genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film the mood states are combined. On the one hand we find well documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits we show emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were shaped in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
In addition, scenes from the CIA's central and other institutions: men brought along who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the office halls, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the object of ridicule, has become a respected director and his manner of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Friendly, Adios" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which action has no place in the city of Boston, where it grew up.
Also, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed old film directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is "frozen" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of taking the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity that at the same time conveys the excitement of the confusion and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on fictional scenes (the imposter team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too many action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematographic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And they are quite well arranged. Sometimes something is added to reality: here everything doesn't come out so elegantly (the scene in which it is facing the crisis at Tehran airport, the deviation of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its track become a madness).
The weakness of Argo is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic trait, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, appreciate its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70's.
But if it collapses, that'll be hard.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is enough.
