At the sight of Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled after the visits to Manning during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was in prison for maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning and noted their answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given by the cells as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, even though the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those problems and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they had not made a record of those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidences' (after they talked about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I hadn't mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Denise Lind Army, also asked Manning why he had not denounced the treatment he received during the meeting in January 2011 with a council to examine the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months before.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "prevention of injuries" regime under which he was present.
The military said that they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, in order to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the older state to know that I was okay and (I wanted to) stop being under injury prevention... in order to enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the sea base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, that cage," Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning stated that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a rink, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming out pointing to his eyes as he slept.
He said that if the concealers couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so he would turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal claim in January 2011 on the treatment he received Manning.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about a claim he had made in the Thursday statement that, after having been forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced to stand naked in front of the captors and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover with the blanket during the counting.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the order given to him by the concealer that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his chalclas to self-injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed their underwear, chalklaces and glasses from their cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted in the war council, which is expected to start early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to make Manning plead guilty of minor crimes and to defend other charges considered too extreme.
The view is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention are justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was retained in accordance with the rules of application for any detainees who are in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from national defence and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
