We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the research published and raising the idea to a discussion group consisting of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desire, but not able, to participate in an activity that fills you".
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do anything but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, says, is "the alteration of the care process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly."
Boring can sound terribly like depression.
