In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of the magazine Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading the article of a magazine.
Some groups heard in the next room a TV program at all volumes that kept no relationship, others heard it with the low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
