On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"A boredom is the way your brain has to tell you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch television, you may be satisfied in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your son is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to shower," says Professor Fenske.
And "this ability to dose applies to other situations," he points out.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we should not be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our way of seeing, we need to be bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate to something worth it," she says.
It points out that what people really seek is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it's hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
