This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this, you have to go down every day to the bottom of your crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth is solidified when you come into contact with the air.
After stripping large sulphur rocks, which total weigh about 70 kilos, it carries them in two bamboo baskets that carry on their shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausting carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb through the turtle, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps not to slip and fall by the cliff.
They know that any transpire could cost them their lives, as a French tourist who spent years at Kawah Ijen's risk.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur they extract
Once above, they pass among tourists photographing them as circus monkeys and, carrying the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little further, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, who pay 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) for each kilogram of sulphur.
Then he sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make waxes, artificial fires, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As normal is to charge 70 kilos, we pull some 46,000 rupees (€3.8) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily doors.
It takes three hours each and ends up wet, but allows you to add 18,000 rupees (11,5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is the triple of what would win in the field.
"The miners' newspaper is very high here, where the collection of coffee is paid at 15,000 rupees (€1.2 euros) on the day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (€167) " , clarify the carrier, who used to work as a butcher on the island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6,2 euros) a day and the coffin was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a weight reason which, in Indonesia, is as striking as the sulphur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to become Islam."
Then he has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing the skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pass her bill despite covering her face with a special mask and glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that fire the volcano.
It's the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I'll work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in English more than acceptable.
Punished by life, this nice and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waitress or receptionist of a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other carriers, it rises every day at two in the morning because the sulphur does not cease to eat at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto goes down to the crater, dawning with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
Some 400 carriers carry the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or supply any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and both the weight.
In fact, they don't even see part of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) charge per camera which, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (€1.2), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the animals and not for the people," protest Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Capable of raising up to 110 kilos, he ensures that he will endure to work "all he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulphur burns the throat and hides the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases ... further, of their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, kneeaches and ankles, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
By rocking the basket over its back, Unainik can now only carry 50 kilos to its 53 years.
Each day, he and his companions take 15 tons of sulphur to the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamasari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat path between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims opening his mouth well, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works carrying sulphur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the harshest trades in the world: the one that makes the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and cost of property and education for not having children.
"The people of Singapore need to grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, we fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unbelievable that these verses are part of an ad of mint pills, but despite that - or perhaps because of that - the video turned viral on YouTube in Singapore early this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references like "Let's put a bay (bollo) in the oven" to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, holds the hope that with the ad they can draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music so people would do their "national duty".
This is something purely from the internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world to reproduce ourselves, so we feel that this was a subject that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as throwing perfumes with pheromones or organizing evenings of quick dates (speed-dating).
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we think, why don't we do as creative as possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1.2 children
What is not taken so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1.300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a city rich and high-tech state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and their strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, according to its national population division, is currently in 1.2 children per woman.
The last time he was above 2 - known as a replacement rate - was 1976.
So why don't Singaporeers have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Division, says that it is due to a "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and forming a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in singleness, and to delay marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
In the meantime, an immigration policy aims to dramatically increase immigration to address the decline of the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore there are websites where xenophobia is barely disguised against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not being integrated.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year the Singapore government party experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with the highest quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling in the birth rate has known effects on the economic growth of a nation, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government tries not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe box", which can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have 46-square-meter surfaces and have been very successful in sales.
However, there is concern that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the El Developers real estate company, says that his "shoe boxes" are sold much faster than the largest units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units wear out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, it admits that the new rules provide clearer guidelines for developers, to whom it used to be blocked if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a State city.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeers working in the financial district of the center seems to have little effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are postponing it," says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another young man about 20 years old.
Men and women mention their career, stress and cost of property and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
